The Roman senate however refused to acknowledge the treaty he had made and, according to the usual custom, gave him up to the Samnites. As soon as he had been delivered up he struck the ambassador who had escorted him to the enemies' line, saying that he was now a Samnite and had broken the ‘jus gentium,' and that the Romans had now a just cause of war against the Samnites.
